 run independently of the transcript extract, so they fire even on a 0-transcript-member pass (which stays attempted-not-succeeded for consolidation, but still re-indexes/decays the on-disk memory set; [#2547](https://github.com/souliane/teatree/issues/2547)). **Phase 4** (`teatree.loops.dream.cross_link`) appends symmetric `[[name]]` wiki-links between related memories — related when their significant-token Jaccard clears a deterministic floor (no model) — and is idempotent (a re-run on an unchanged set adds nothing). **Phase 4b** (`teatree.loops.dream.merge`, [#2723](https://github.com/souliane/teatree/issues/2723)) is the on-disk MERGE verb cross-link was missing: it collapses a near-duplicate PAIR (body-token Jaccard ≥ 0.85 AND same frontmatter `type`/`name` family — far above cross-link's floor) into the HIGHER-WEIGHT survivor (a BINDING rule outranks a plain restatement, so binding doctrine is never the side absorbed), appends the absorbed file's distinct lines with a provenance header, and ARCHIVES the absorbed file via `decay._archive_one` (moved, never deleted) so the re-index drops its pointer in the same pass. **Decision-3 (binding):** two BINDING near-duplicates are NEVER auto-merged — they are cross-linked and a deduped `dream-binding-reconcile` ticket is filed via the existing `promote_memory` filer (reusing its banned-term / bare-reference withholding) for human reconciliation. Phase 4b runs AFTER cross-link, BEFORE re-index, LIVE by default behind the `[loops.dream] merge` / `T3_DREAM_MERGE` kill-switch, and is fault-isolated. The whole file-side phase orchestration (4/4b/5/6 + the § 4 gates) is a composed `teatree.loops.dream.phase_runner.MemoryPhaseRunner`. **Phase 5** (`teatree.loops.dream.reindex`) regenerates `MEMORY.md` as one tight line per memory — a single bare `name.md` pointer (no `[name.md](name.md)` href duplication) plus a ≤120-char summary, the WHOLE line capped at 160 chars so it stays under the gate-(d) load budget — deduped, filename-stable, content stays in the topic file, byte-identical on a no-change re-run. **Phase 6** (`teatree.loops.dream.decay`) ages a memory out by ARCHIVING it (moved to `<memory_dir>/archive/` with a provenance header, never deleted) — gated by a NON-VACUOUS retention guard that retains a memory when ANY of: it is fresh (mtime within the window), it is still referenced (another live memory or the index `[[name]]`-links it), OR — the **transfer-before-prune rail** ([#2546](https://github.com/souliane/teatree/issues/2546), #1933 § 2) — its lesson has NO confirmed durable home in the `ConsolidatedMemory` ledger. Only a memory that is old AND unreferenced AND durably homed is archived; a guard-disabled probe proves each guard has teeth. The §2 rail — *"delete an index line only after the fact has a confirmed durable home in a topic file"* — is applied to the topic file itself: an injected `HomeResolver` seam keeps the file-side mechanics DB-free under test, while the production `ledger_durable_home_resolver` reads `ConsolidatedMemory.objects.prunable()` (the index-pruner's terminal-status + recorded-`durable_destination` surface) once per pass and maps a topic file to a row by path membership in `source_files` OR by its name appearing in a `durable_destination`. **Budget RETIRE tier ([#2723](https://github.com/souliane/teatree/issues/2723)).** The `prunable()` home-rail is structurally EMPTY for the hand-authored corpus (0 ledger rows reference on-disk memories), so it can never archive the files that bloat the index. A second, ledger-INDEPENDENT tier (opt-in via `DecayPolicy(budget_tier=BudgetTier())`, enabled in the cron) fires ONLY when `MEMORY.md` is over the gate-(d) load budget and archives files that are (a) older than a 90-day ceiling — by a LOGICAL `lesson_updated` frontmatter clock, NOT raw `st_mtime`, so a cross-link / re-index rewrite does not reset the decay clock — (b) unreferenced, and (c) whose lesson is CAPTURED ELSEWHERE (a near-duplicate survivor exists — a content/duplication check, never the empty `prunable()` join); a genuinely unique lesson is always retained. The cron re-indexes AFTER this decay so `MEMORY.md` falls back under the gate-(d) budget in the SAME pass. All phases accept an explicit `memory_dir` and never touch the real `~/.claude` under test. **Phase 3b** ([#2346](https://github.com/souliane/teatree/issues/2346)) closes the drift → live-eval loop: `teatree.loops.dream.eval_proposer` maps each grounded cluster to an eval CANDIDATE in a JSONL review queue, then `teatree.loops.dream.promote` PROMOTES it to a real `under_load` scenario (`evals/scenarios/promoted_drift.yaml` + `_pass`/`_fail` replay fixtures) — the artifacts the deterministic replay gate and the weekly metered lane run unchanged. The nightly `tick` requests proposals **LIVE by default** (the `[loops.dream] propose_evals` / `T3_DREAM_PROPOSE_EVALS` kill-switch flips it off). Promotion is auto but gated by a **non-bypassable anti-vacuity guard** (`promote.guard_can_fail`): it runs the real grader (`teatree.eval.report.evaluate`) against a synthesised drift-recommitting transcript and promotes only when that verdict is FAIL (the matchers have teeth) AND a compliant transcript grades PASS (not a tautology); a candidate whose grader cannot fail is rejected — no file written. The guard is deterministic; live metered grading of a promoted scenario lands with the weekly Agent-SDK lane. **Phase 3b LLM derivation** ([#2447](https://github.com/souliane/teatree/issues/2447)) is the richer, **default-OFF** follow-up to the fixed-matcher `promote`: `teatree.loops.dream.llm_eval_proposer` runs an injected LLM synthesizer that turns a grounded candidate plus its cited transcript slice into a COMPLETE `under_load` `EvalSpec` — a pollution preamble saturated to the documented ~28k-char envelope floor, discriminating positive + negative matchers, and a judge rubric — parsed through the real loader and gated by a **candidate-derived** teeth check (`teatree.loops.dream._teeth_check.teeth_check_against_candidate`): it synthesises the `_fail`/`_pass` transcripts FROM the candidate's OWN cited drift and compliant tool-call shapes and grades both through the suite's real grader (`teatree.eval.report.evaluate`), DROPPING a spec whose matchers do not reject the candidate's own cited drift (or reject its compliant shape as a tautology) — proving the matchers target the SPECIFIC drift the candidate describes, not `promote`'s fixed session.py-edit transcripts. Even a proven spec is never autonomously committed to `evals/scenarios`: `stage_derived_evals` writes a staging `derived_evals.yaml` a human / standing core-maker ratifies via a PR. The phase is OFF unless the `[loops.dream] derive_evals` / `T3_DREAM_DERIVE_EVALS` toggle is set, so an unflagged pass is byte-identical. The `dream` mini-loop is registered `off_live_tick` (driven only by its own cron); `t3 doctor` surfaces the 48h staleness alarm.
 
 `Ticket` also carries a `Role` enum (`AUTHOR` / `REVIEWER`) orthogonal to its state. The reviewer role drives the §5.6 `reviewer_prs` scanner (`Ticket(role="reviewer", issue_url=<pr_url>)`) and short-circuits to `delivered` once the review work completes; the author role is the default lifecycle.
 
